Tools You'll Need
Recording
Loom — you already have it, good for getting started
Limitation is Loom is designed for screen recording and talking head — fine for early episodes
Longer term you'll want Riverside.fm or Squadcast for higher quality audio/video recording especially if you bring guests in remotely
OBS Studio — free, professional grade, worth learning for more control
Audio — The Most Important Thing
YouTube audiences forgive average video
They will not forgive bad audio
Minimum — Blue Yeti or Rode NT-USB microphone
Acoustic treatment — even moving to a small room with soft furnishings makes a dramatic difference
This is the single highest ROI investment for the channel
Video
Modern iPhone or Android is genuinely sufficient to start
Simple ring light — under $50, transforms talking head quality immediately
Tripod — basic, essential
Editing
DaVinci Resolve — free, professional grade, industry standard
CapCut — faster learning curve, good for early episodes
For a series like this you'll want chapter markers and clean cuts — not heavy effects
Graphics and Visuals
Canva — thumbnails, title cards, episode graphics
Thumbnail quality on YouTube is disproportionately important for click through rate
The Thread brand needs a consistent visual identity from episode one
Research and Scripting
Me — for exactly what we've been doing
Notion or Obsidian — for organizing episode notes, thread connections, research
Keep a running document of threads left open at end of each episode
Distribution
YouTube — primary platform
Spotify and Apple Podcasts — audio only version of each episode, doubles your reach for zero extra work
X/Twitter — defense community is extremely active there, natural audience
LinkedIn — given your professional background, high value channel for this content

